y and his family's experiences on a reserve. Through an original retelling of the Indigenous commercial and social networks that existed in the northeast before European contact, the author explains that the Wendat Confederacy was at the geopolitical centre of a commonwealth based on peace, trade, and reciprocity. This network, he argues, was a true democracy, where all beings of all natures were equally valued and respected and where women kept their place at the centre of their families and communities. Identifying Canada's first civilizations as the originators of modern democracy, Eatenonha represents a continuing quest to heal and educate all peoples through an Indigenous way of comprehending life and the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWyandot IndianszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800046440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228000464423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228000464/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles